This article provides a theoretical and empirical insight on the study of 
population aging in India, with the special reference to the causes that have 
made it extremely significant. It evidently looks into the factors that are 
extensively associated with the process of population aging and have contributed 
to the Indian society. Demographically speaking, in the Indian context, the 
process of demographic transition has resulted from a falling birth rate, a 
slowing death rate, and spike in life expectancy. In the context of developing 
countries, the concept of population aging has been brought from developed 
countries. Initially, the outcomes of demographic transition had been 
experienced by developed regions followed by the rest of the world. Finally, it 
examines the consequences of complications that arise due to growth in life 
expectancy at birth, and further suggests the probable remedies to both strategy 
